South African Equities: Anglo, BHP Billiton, SacOil, Vivendi

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-04-08T12:25:16Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-08/south-african-equities-anglo-bhp-billiton-sacoil-vivendi.html
South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index headed for a third week of gains, rising 215.61, or
0.7 percent, to 32,848.86 at 1:47 p.m. in Johannesburg, taking
the week’s increase to 1.4 percent.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo American Plc (AAL)  , the diversified mining company
that makes up 11 percent of South Africa’s benchmark stock
index, gained 6 rand, or 1.7 percent, to 359 rand. Copper
rallied for a fourth day and zinc climbed on optimism global
economic growth will sustain demand for industrial metals. Lead
advanced to the highest level in three years and aluminum
reached the highest price since April 2008.  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s largest mining
company, climbed to the highest in a month, jumping 5.23 rand,
or 1.9 percent, to 280.33 rand.  SacOil Holdings Ltd. (SCL SJ), an oil and natural gas
exploration company, snapped two days of gains, losing 7 cents,
or 3.4 percent, to 1.98 rand. The company said it has started
trading its shares on the Alternative Investment Market of the
London Stock Exchange.  Vivendi Income Fund Ltd. (VIF SJ), a commercial, retail and
industrial property investor, rallied the most since it listed
in November, gaining 29 cents, or 6.1 percent, to 5.01 rand.
Vivendi said it will distribute a maiden payment of 9.96 cents
per linked unit to shareholders for the first half through
February.  To contact the reporter on this story:
